Read my full release for more on how this bill allows business owners to spend their money to fix problems and improve accessibility, rather than paying off lawyers to settle cookie cutter lawsuits: 
https://t.co/MISvIjaEPh https://t.co/1wYyhjdkZY

Watch my full speech on how the commonsense fixes in the ADA Education and Reform Act will help improve access. It addresses a lot of the concerns raised by disability advocates: https://t.co/4DSoP12unH

❌ This bill does not weaken the rights of the disabled.
✔️ The bill facilitates the removal of barriers to ensure better access in a shorter period of time and discourages quick payoff lawsuits that do nothing for access.

❌ This bill does not shift the burden of compliance from business to victims.
✔️ The bill still requires businesses to comply with ADA. The only difference for victims is whether they provide notice or file a lawsuit.

❌ This bill does not relieve business of their obligation to comply with the ADA. 
✔️ Public accommodations are still responsible for ensuring access, must respond to violation notices, and can be sued if they do not improve access.

❌ This bill will not turn anyone into a second class citizen. 
✔️This bill extends "notice and cure" requirements that already apply to other civil rights laws.
Today we provided the same corrections at the federal level. Let me be clear: this bill does not shield businesses or public accommodations from complying with the ADA. Here's the breakdown:

The bipartisan CA bill:
✔ gives business 120 days to fix violations
✔ educates business owners on compliance 
✔ redirects payouts toward improving access
✔ protects against serial lawsuits
SB 269 was authored by a Democratic State Senator, passed by a Democratic majority legislature, and signed into law by Governor Brown in 2016.
We hear these stories all the time-- lawsuits being settled without violations being fixed--so much, that state governments have acted to curb this abuse. CA Democrats have led this fight.
The only winner was the lawyer who was filing the same cookie cutter lawsuit all around town.

A small restaurant in downtown San Diego tells this story: It was sued by a lawyer who had filed 50 ADA suits against San Diego Country restaurants in one year. Though no violations existed, proving it in court would have cost $50,000 or more, So they paid $2,500 to settle.
A few bad actors are abusing the ADA, exploiting this landmark civil rights law for personal financial gain. No one disputes this abuse is happening or says this increases access.
Today, the House passed the ADA Education and Reform Act-- a bipartisan bill I helped introduce to ensure businesses can spend money on access not lawyers.

text:
If Congress can't do its job and pass a budget, we shouldn't get paid. The shutdown showed us what happens when we rely on short-term budgets – we hurt our research institutions, military, and economy. 
https://t.co/uOoOPD0wGA
Our work is far from over and I hope we can get to work on long-term solutions to our nation's challenges.

We also need to provide real certainty to Dreamers. The President, Speaker Ryan, and now Senate Majority Leader McConnell have said they want to find a path forward for Dreamers and there are several bipartisan bills in both the House and the Senate that deserve a vote.

As a former member of the Armed Services Committee, I've spent a lot of time talking to military leaders in San Diego about their challenges and they've consistently said continuing resolutions cripple our readiness.

Defense Secretary Mattis has warned continuing resolutions lead to lost training time, delayed ship maintenance and personnel gaps for our military. 

https://t.co/XWIfEiKYAl

Short-term funding means science and research institutions need to delay current studies. They also can't plan for future research opportunities. 
https://t.co/D9PBVDEWQ8

I opposed another short-term extension that fails to provide our military, research institutions, and employers the certainty they need to ensure our national defense, protect public health, and grow our economy.

https://t.co/83DhiRJDaL https://t.co/HVdOd5LxmS
